======================================================================
PART 3: GROWTH RATES — BOTH GROW EXPONENTIALLY
======================================================================

  Fibonacci growth rate: phi = 1.618034
  Pascal 3-strand growth rate per step: 4^(1/3) = 1.587401
  Pascal 3-strand growth rate per 3 steps: 4 (doubling of central binomial)

  Fibonacci per 3 steps: phi^3 = 4.236068
  Pascal per 3 steps: 4
  Ratio: 4/phi^3 = 0.944272

  Fibonacci per 6 steps: phi^6 = 17.944272
  Pascal per 6 steps: 4^2 = 16
  Ratio: 16/phi^6 = 0.891649

  4^(1/3) = 1.587401 vs phi = 1.618034
  Fibonacci per step is FASTER! phi > 4^(1/3)
  So P/F ratio should DECREASE over time.
  k=6: P/F = 1.250000
  k=12: P/F = 0.875000
  k=18: P/F = 0.664087
  k=24: P/F = 0.524284

======================================================================
PART 4: THE 6-CYCLE AND TOURNAMENT THEORY
======================================================================

  WHY 6?
  The 3-strand Pascal has period 3 (from the 3 strands).
  The Fibonacci has period 2 (even/odd symmetry from n -> -n involution).
  Their LCM is 6.

  In tournament theory:
  - 3 = the fundamental odd cycle (3-cycle)
  - 2 = the arc binary choice (and the OCF fugacity)
  - 6 = LCM(3,2) = the "full period" of the combined structure

  This 6 appears as:
  - h(G2) = 6 (Coxeter number of the exceptional Lie algebra G2)
  - 6 = C(4,2) = number of arcs at n=4
  - 6 = 3! = number of labeled transitive tournaments on 3 vertices
  - The GS DOF formula has period related to floor((n-1)/2)

  THE DEEP REASON:
  3 and 2 are the GENERATORS of the theory.
  3-cycles generate tournament complexity.
  2-fold arc choice generates tournament variety.
  Their interaction has period LCM(3,2) = 6.


